80–1239","–1182":"–1182","1239":"1239","1238":"1238","1159":"1159","1223":"1223","before 1199":"before 1199","from 1175 to 1182":"from 1175 to 1182","1150":"1150","1209":"1209","1182":"1182","1180":"1180","Chaumont-en-Vexin, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France":"Chaumont-en-Vexin, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France","Chaumont-en-Vexin, Oise, Picardie, France":"Chaumont-en-Vexin, Oise, Picardie, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Chaumont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gilles, Raoul, Yvon.  Spanish Alicia, Andres, Arturo, Beatriz, Elia, Jose, Julio, Miguel, Raul.","French: habitational name from any of numerous places called Chaumont ‘bald mountain’ (ultimately from Latin <i>calvus mons</i>), for example in Cher, Orne, Jura, Haute-Savoie.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Chaumont in Orne (see 1 above)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"en","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Juel.","Norwegian (<b>Øen</b>): habitational name from the farm name Øen, found in several places. In Hornindal in Nordfjord and in Ål in Hallingdal it is from <i>øy</i> ‘meadow by water’, in Hyllestad in Sunnfjord from <i>å</i> ‘small river’ + Old Norse <i>vin</i> ‘meadow’, in other places from the definite singular form of <i>øy</i> ‘island’.","Norwegian: habitational name from the farm name Oen in Hordaland, from Old Norse <i>Ó</i>, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Wen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Chi, Han, Cheng, Jin, Li, Yen, Yong, Chen, Chih-Hung, Chin, Hong, Jian, Jung, Long, Huan, Hung, Hung Chi, Ly, Quan.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 溫, meaning ‘warm’ in Chinese: (i) from Wen (溫), the name of an ancient state during the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ). During the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) this state was annexed by the state of Di and the prince of Wen fled to the state of Wey (located around present-day Hebi and Xinxiang in Henan province). His descendants acquired 溫, the name of their original state, as their surname. (ii) from the placename Wen (溫), the name of a fief granted to Wen Ji (溫季), an official in the state of Jin (located mainly in present-day Shanxi province) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iii) from the Chi Wen (叱溫), Wen Pen (溫盆), and Wen Gu (溫孤) families of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China. (iv) from the personal name of Wen Sheng (溫昇), who went into exile and changed his original surname, Liu (劉), to Wen 溫 after his father, Liu Yicong (劉易從), an official in the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ), suffered persecution and death."]}]},{"name":"Vexin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Vane  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vane","meanings":["English (Kent):","variant of   Vanes  .","variant of   Fayne   with southern English voicing of initial [f] to [v]."]}]},{"name":"Hugues","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Hugues Capet  (  ?93